diagram_notes.content: This delay is set to ensure that the URL analysis in the ANY.RUN Sandbox is completed before proceeding with the next step in the Tines Story.
If the URL submission to the ANY.RUN Sandbox fails for any reason, you will receive an email notification containing the response code and error message.
If the analysis URL in the ANY.RUN Sandbox fails for any reason, you will receive an email notification with an error message.

This Story automates the analysis of suspicious URL and generates reports using the ANY.RUN Sandbox.

To use this Story, you need an ANY.RUN account with a plan level of at least "Hunter". You also have to add your API key to your credentials in Tines. 

If the URL analysis in the ANY.RUN Sandbox determines that the verdict is "not clean", you will receive an email notification containing the analysis results, detected IoC's and a link to the full report.

For more information about how the ANY.RUN Sandbox works, please visit https://app.any.run/docs
To submit a URL to ANY.RUN Sandbox, you can choose the method that best suits your needs: either through a submission form or via a webhook.

In the "Define Parameters" action, you can configure additional settings for the analysis. These settings will be applied during URL submission and forwarded to the subsequent HTTP Request action, "Submit a URL in the ANY.RUN Sandbox."

Here is a brief overview of the available parameters:

- **obj_type**: Specifies the type of the new task (the value "url" is required for this workflow).
- **opt_timeout**: Defines the timeout option for the analysis.
- **obj_ext_browser**: Indicates the browser name to use.
- **env_os**: Specifies the operating system.
- **env_bitness**: Defines the bitness of the operating system.
- **env_version**: Sets the version of the operating system.
- **opt_automated_interactivity**: Controls the automated interactivity (ML) option (changing this is not recommended).
- **auto_confirm_uac**: Enables automatic confirmation of Windows UAC requests (changing this is not recommended).

For a complete list of possible values or to configure other analysis parameters, refer to the ANY.RUN API documentation at: https://any.run/api-documentation. Alternatively, you can define these parameters directly within the HTTP Request action, "Submit a URL in the ANY.RUN Sandbox."

Note: If you define additional parameters in the "Define Parameters" action, ensure they are properly mapped in the "Submit a URL in the ANY.RUN Sandbox" action.
Submit the main analysis object (URL) to the ANY.RUN Sandbox using the configuration parameters specified in "Define Parameters". This action will return the Task ID of the newly created analysis.

Upon completion of the object analysis in the ANY.RUN Sandbox, a detailed report is generated.

If the object is determined to be unsafe, this Story enables the automation of report retrieval and follow-up response actions. We recommend examining the analysis results through the HTML report, which offers in-depth insights into the object's behavior within an isolated environment. This includes details on network activity, system modifications, files created or altered, and processes executed.

Beyond the primary report, the ANY.RUN Sandbox automatically extracts Indicators of Compromise (IoCs), such as IP addresses, URLs, and file hashes. These IoCs are aggregated from the analysis outcomes and presented in a dedicated table for ease of reference.

Based on the actions performed in the Story, the "Build Results" compiles the outcomes from all stages of the analysis.

In addition to a concise summary of the object, "Build Results" contains the HTML report, an IoC table, and the complete raw report in JSON format.

You can configure integration with other solutions you use and create automated threat response workflows based on the analysis results from ANY.RUN Sandbox. Finally, you will receive an email containing all the information included in the "Build Results" action.
